title: Mike Kelly's Dual Bowden E3Dv5 RoBo 3D X Carriage Mod

description.text:
Note: this version is old and out of date. It will require additional work to use with the E3Dv6. Use my modular carriage instead
==================== What this is:
Converts the stock RoBo 3D printer with a single direct feed extruder and replaces it with dual bowden extruder with no loss in x travel. This is just the x-carriage as the cold end will be released separately Background: I have designed and fabricated, with the help of tessarect, a dual extruder upgrade to the RoBo 3D printer. As many RoBo 3D owners make the upgrade to a E3D all metal hot end, it makes sense that instead of going from stock hot end to kraken, many users will want to go stock hot end > single E3D > dual E3D to save cost on parts. With that in mind this mod is directed at the latter group of people. If you are on the stock robo 3d hot end and want to upgrade to multi-extruders, I HIGHLY recommend not doing this mod but rather wait for me to release the kraken version. The kraken is smaller, lighter weight, easier to adjust, and provides more options later on. This mod is just inteded for people with an existing E3D looking to add a second. See instructions for BOM and install guide

The entire build documentation can be viewed here: https://cloudup.com/cGGfhsMgMnd BOM: Printed:
1x X carriage
1x Fan Shroud
1x Flow Director
1x Fan Holder
2x J-Head Saddle
2x J-Head Mount Hardware:
4x LM8UU Linear Bearings: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00ED150S4/ref=oh_details_o08_s00_i00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 4x M4 - 25mm Length Screws: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B000FN1VB4/ref=oh_details_o05_s01_i00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 4x M4 Lock Nut: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B000NBKLKA/ref=oh_details_o09_s01_i00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 4x M4 Nut: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B009EGJT3A/ref=oh_details_o07_s03_i02?ie=UTF8&psc=1 4x Compression Spring: http://www.mcmaster.com/#9657k274/=rc2wv5 4x M3-25mm length screw: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B000FN7W6W/ref=oh_details_o05_s00_i02?ie=UTF8&psc=1 4x M3 Nut: http://www.amazon.com/Steel-M3-0-5-Threads-Made-Pack/dp/B000NBIH92/ref=pd_sim_indust_1?ie=UTF8&refRID=128RW9M8XQVSPV73G65A 4x M3-16mm length screw: For Part Fan, Use stock robo 3d fan screws or cut M3-25 down 6x Self Tapping Screw for fan shroud: Stock with E3D 1x M3-20mm length screw and lock nut: From stock carriage Phase 1: Remove the stock x-carriage Watch the build videos to understand how to remove x-carriage from linear rails. youtube.com/watch?v=CtCjLwwDUj4 Phase 2: Assemble the dual x-carriage Steps will be outlined here in more detail shortly Phase 3: Install the x carriage Steps will be outlined here in more detail shortly Phase 4: Reinstall x axis and calibrate Steps will be outlined here in more detail shortly

description.text:

But it should work for anything with a square 4-hole pattern. Spacing of the holes can be adjusted within the SCAD file. Height is adjusted by sliding the inserts up and down within the slides, then tightening the corresponding screw. I have included my file, with the cooling fan mount, and one without it as well. Many things are adjustable within the SCAD file. Edit 4-17-14: Added Rev 02 with thicker sidewalls and slightly enlarged zip-tie holes.

Requires two 4-40 screws and nuts.  Zip-ties are useful to tie down hoses and wires.  
This plan involves placing the cooling fan inside the bracket, then mounting this to the outside.  A thinner fan than whatever came with the original Eventorbot may be required.  
Spacing between nozzles (center-to-center) with the attached STLs is 30mm, but can be adjusted within the file.

Snap style wire or cable holder. Has screw/bolt hole to attach to whatever you need to hold wire or cable for.
Print with supports on it's side.

description.text:
y endstop bracket for mendelmax with the Y slide from trinity labs.
Edit: Added scad, changed to M2.5 screws.  They fit through the switch, just tight.

USE SUPPORT MATERIAL! -- I forgot to when I added this to a platter of other parts.  It printed better than I expected, but that wasn't what it was designed for.
Currently using switch SS-3GL13P.
Attach switch with M2.5x14 bolts / nuts. There are nut traps in the back. The bracket screws into a t-slot nut with M5x10s.
This mount is meant to stop the carriage before collision, not before the head is off the usable build area.  If you have firmware like Marlin that can home outside the build area, this is what you should want.  If you aren't using firmware that can do that, get better firmware, use a different endstop that is adjustable, or just don't worry about it and let slic3r constrain the print area while the firmware protects the machine.

title: Vibration Isolating Silicone Dampers
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
updated STLs - added tabs to make it easier to pull them apart These are molds for casting vibration isolating dampers for use in multi rotor applications. Folks that have built out the QAV400 or the ADS-400Q (and other variants of those models) will know what these are and why this mold is useful. Shopping list:
M3 6mm hex bolts (or 8mm bolts if you have thicker plates)
M3 washers
M4 washers CA the M3 washers to the heads of the bolts (on the top of the head, not threaded onto the shoulder). This will give the silicone an extra surface to bite on to. Before placing the parts in the mold - spray on a release agent (if you have a 3D printer then you already have release agent - it's called hair spray :). After the part's been cast and cured. take the M4 washer and CA it to the shoulder and voila - vibration dampers :) You'll need 2 part silicone casting material, and you're shooting for a durometer of 30 on the Shore A scale. Use a 20ML disposable syringe to inject the material into the mold..then let it sit and cure. Once it's cured - remove the top of the mold then trim with a sharp pair of scissors. Enjoy :)

description.text: This is a human powered air horn!

Print out the horn and the cap. Drill a 1/4" hole on the end of the flat part, on the outside of the horn, where the recessed circle is. (2" from end) ( Make sure you only drill through the first layer of plastic, and not all the way through to the center)Then cut a circle out of a latex balloon that is large enough to cover the end. Place the balloon tight across the end that has an inner and outer shell. Then place cap on same end. Then blow into hole that you drilled and make some noise!!! Notes: Make sure the balloon is tight across the end with no wrinkles!
You also might have to clean out the inside of the horn where the plastic has bridged. I have not tested this design, so it might or might not work. Although it will most likely work. Please let me know if you build it and let me know how well it works...thanks Updates: I have updated the airhorn file to make it easier to drill the hole. (this is to just make things easier for you) I have also added the sketchup files in case you would like to modify my design.

title: Hollow cylinder for filament holder made with a stand

description.text:
This OpenScad module defines a hollow cylinder with parameters (outside, inside, length) that can be used for filament spooling. Using a retort stand It is always better to have the filament roll on top of the extruder. If you got a high ceiling or if you are moving your printer, then you need a portable solution. Together with a "chemistry stand" it will make a fine filament roll holder. Buy a retort stand, i.e. the kind that is used in chemistry labs. Yours could be made of:
  • Two 1.2m vertical bars (with two attached "feet" or else attachable feet). You can take shorter vertical bars (e.g. 0.9m,) but then the horizotal bar may be at your eye-level ---
  • One horizontal 1m bar onto which you then can glide the roll.
  • Two connectors for fixing the horizontal bar. It is best to buy ones that allow to lift the horizontal bar quickly.
    • Other A hollow cylinder can be of use with several other filament spoolers.

Printer:

Felix 1.0, 2.0 and Pro1

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.25

Infill:

30%

Notes: Any resolution and any infill from 20 to 80 % can do. This one of the rare objects where these parameters don't matter much. Use at least 3 contour walls (I'd say 4 is better).

Configure the OpenScad program and print a hollow cylinder so that the roll can turn with less effort. Attached pictures show the principle. The STL examples included are for a 12mm bar and either a roll with a 31.6 mm hole or one with a 38.4mm hole. Unfortunately the filament roll holes come in many sizes. Read Richard Horne's attempt to promote an universal size (http://richrap.blogspot.ch/2014/03/universal-3d-printing-filament-spool.html). Customize Use the customizer to specify your size. Hole diameter is 1.2 for a typical retort stand. Filament roll hole diameters seem to vary from 19 to 74 mm. Frequent ones are 31mm, 39mm and 52mm. Outersize diameter ranges from 12.5cm (e.g. Taulman T-glase) to 30cm. Typical outer width (length of the cylinder to print) is from 6cm to 12.5cm. This piece can be printed with any 3D printer in any quality. I suggest to use some kind of moderate fill. The printer on the picture is a Felix for which I made the cylinder. Cylinders can be printed in any plastic (except TPE). PLA is probably the best solution since its easy to print, cheap, little friction and fairly smooth surface. I was surprised at how smoothly the filament reels now turn. Tips for slicing and post-processing
  • Use a file for smoothing the inside
  • A 3.7 x 19.5 cm cylinder can take many hours to print and there are no reasons for working with high quality settings. Printing with 0.25mm is really fine enough. It is more important that the cylinders are round. Therefore, go slowly with the first 2 layers.
    • In addition, one also could print 2 short extra-cylinders, insert before and after the big one and then use clamps to hold in position (for long "night printings"), but after a few years I stopped using these. If the horizontal bar is horizontal the reel should not slip sideways. PS:
  • Of course, publishing a hollow cylinder is not worth a "thing" here, but I am really happy with my chemistry stand solution :)
    • Updates
  • Update 24/8/2012: Been using this for over a week now. I still like the setup a lot, but I reprinted the cylinder in better quality using PLA and added clamps. The roll now turns even more easily and can't slip off after a many hours of printing.
  • Update 26/10/2012: I am doing unsupervised 24h prints with this setup. Convinced :) The only remaining trouble is irregular filament, but that's a different issue ...
  • Update Feb 2016. I still am using this system. I also made it OK for the customizer.

author: NilsRoe

title: 3d print coated with solid copper metal

description.text: The regular ABS print was painted with conductive copper paint and then had a thin layer of copper deposited over it using electroforming. The process is similar to electroplating, but the metal coating is much thicker. The ultimate goal is to electroform a thick enough layer that the ABS print could be dissolved out leaving just the metal. This is my first attempt at electroforming (the first one worth showing off anyway). This thing was featured on the 3D Printing Today podcast available on iTunes, Stitcher radio or direct from the source at http://threedprintingtoday.libsyn.com/

comments.text: I think removing the print with a solvent would be better than heat so either ABS or PLA could be used, but ABS is probably preferable because its solvents are a little friendlier.

Fan Duct for a 50mm fan, with an arm mount for attaching to a hot end.  
The location and size of the mount hole on the fan duct itself can be adjusted within the SCAD file.  It can also be adjusted to be ether a single mount or dual mount if desired.  I mean that it can be either two mounts to straddle a single mount point, or else one mount point for two others to straddle.  
Current STLs are set for an 8mm inner mount width.  
The arm mount is likewise adjustable for different hole sizes, length, width, and single vs. double style.
I added arms to an existing STL.  It was a pretty complicated STL, so give it time to render and slice.

This is yet another display stand for Emmett's Three Cube Gears http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:213946. See also http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:95706 and http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:39054. I hope I haven't missed anyone. This one is very simple and fits in a small printing area - by necessity for me! It allows me to even show off my cube when it's distorted - the many moods of the cube! Since all diagonals of the cube (2" on an edge) are not necessarily printed equal, I include two little adjustment pads that can slip into place - gluing optional - if your cube is a bit small in your favorite configuration.

I printed with 0.3 mm layers, 2 shells, and 20% fill. Space on the plate is so fully utilized that you cannot use the loops your printer might normally include as primers for printing. If you have any trouble slicing these files, just remove the loops.  
After printing, the arch should be glued into the base, lining up near the center of the base the indentations in the arch into which the corners of the cube nestle. A glue that seems to work better on PLA is Elmer's Model + Hobby Cement, but superglue is OK, too. In fact, glue is not entirely necessary in a quiet environment. If the cube is too loosely supported, one or both adjustment pads can be slipped into place (or also glued in).
